# Simple Linear Regression {#sec-simple}

## Model Specification

We regress **miles per gallon** (`mpg`) on **weight** (`wt`).

$$
\text{mpg}_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{wt}_i + \varepsilon_i
$$

```{python}
#| label: slr-model

model_slr = smf.ols("mpg ~ wt", data=mtcars).fit()
print(model_slr.summary())
```

## Interpreting the Output

| Term | Estimate | Interpretation |
|------|----------|----------------|
| Intercept | ~37.29 | Expected `mpg` when `wt = 0` (extrapolation) |
| `wt` | ~−5.34 | Each additional 1,000 lbs → mpg drops by ~5.34 |

> **R² ≈ 0.75**: Weight alone explains ~75% of the variance in fuel efficiency.

## Scatter Plot with Regression Line

```{python}
#| label: slr-plot
#| fig-cap: "Simple Linear Regression: mpg ~ wt"

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.scatter(mtcars["wt"], mtcars["mpg"], color="#4C72B0", alpha=0.7, edgecolors="white", s=70)

x_range = np.linspace(mtcars["wt"].min(), mtcars["wt"].max(), 100)
y_pred  = model_slr.params["Intercept"] + model_slr.params["wt"] * x_range
ax.plot(x_range, y_pred, color="#DD4444", linewidth=2, label="OLS fit")

ax.set_xlabel("Weight (1000 lbs)")
ax.set_ylabel("Miles per Gallon")
ax.set_title("mpg ~ wt")
ax.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

