# Model Diagnostics {#sec-diagnostics}

Reliable OLS inference requires checking four key assumptions.

## Residuals vs Fitted

```{python}
#| label: resid-fitted
#| fig-cap: "Residuals vs Fitted — checking linearity & homoscedasticity"

fitted   = model_mlr.fittedvalues
residuals = model_mlr.resid

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.scatter(fitted, residuals, color="#4C72B0", alpha=0.7, edgecolors="white", s=60)
ax.axhline(0, linestyle="--", color="gray")
ax.set_xlabel("Fitted Values")
ax.set_ylabel("Residuals")
ax.set_title("Residuals vs Fitted")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

## Q-Q Plot (Normality of Residuals)

```{python}
#| label: qq-plot
#| fig-cap: "Q-Q Plot — residuals should follow the diagonal for normality"

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sm.qqplot(residuals, line="s", ax=ax, alpha=0.6)
ax.set_title("Normal Q-Q Plot of Residuals")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

## Breusch-Pagan Test (Homoscedasticity)

```{python}
#| label: bp-test

X_exog = sm.add_constant(mtcars[["wt", "hp", "cyl"]])
bp_stat, bp_p, _, _ = het_breuschpagan(model_mlr.resid, X_exog)

print(f"Breusch-Pagan statistic : {bp_stat:.4f}")
print(f"p-value                 : {bp_p:.4f}")
print("→ Homoscedasticity assumed." if bp_p > 0.05
      else "→ Evidence of heteroscedasticity (consider robust SEs).")
```

## Variance Inflation Factors (Multicollinearity)

```{python}
#| label: vif

vif_data = pd.DataFrame({
    "Feature": ["wt", "hp", "cyl"],
    "VIF": [
        variance_inflation_factor(X_exog.values, i+1)
        for i in range(3)
    ]
}).round(2)

vif_data["Flag"] = vif_data["VIF"].apply(
    lambda v: "⚠️ High" if v > 10 else ("🔶 Moderate" if v > 5 else "✅ OK")
)
vif_data
```

> **Rule of thumb:** VIF > 10 signals severe multicollinearity; VIF > 5 warrants attention.

