# Logistic Regression {#sec-logistic}

For a binary outcome, we switch to **logistic regression**. Here we predict whether a car has manual transmission (`am = 1`).

$$
\log\!\left(\frac{p}{1-p}\right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1\,\text{mpg} + \beta_2\,\text{wt}
$$

```{python}
#| label: logit-model

model_logit = smf.logit("am ~ mpg + wt", data=mtcars).fit()
print(model_logit.summary())
```

## Predicted Probabilities

```{python}
#| label: logit-probs
#| fig-cap: "Predicted probability of manual transmission"

mtcars["prob_manual"] = model_logit.predict()

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sc = ax.scatter(
    mtcars["wt"], mtcars["mpg"],
    c=mtcars["prob_manual"], cmap="RdYlGn",
    s=80, edgecolors="white", vmin=0, vmax=1
)
fig.colorbar(sc, ax=ax, label="P(Manual)")
ax.set_xlabel("Weight (1000 lbs)")
ax.set_ylabel("Miles per Gallon")
ax.set_title("Predicted P(am = 1) from Logistic Regression")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

## Odds Ratios

```{python}
#| label: odds-ratios

odds_ratios = pd.DataFrame({
    "OR":   np.exp(model_logit.params),
    "2.5%": np.exp(model_logit.conf_int()[0]),
    "97.5%":np.exp(model_logit.conf_int()[1])
}).round(3)

odds_ratios
```

